<P><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr. Jingles</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I am concerned about the potential for collection of usage statistics based on ip and time.  OE is currently designed to inform slicer when it starts and stops on a computer.  If this data were to be stolen or leaked out then Mythic could crosscheck the ips and access times and ban users.  I realize I could block this with iptables or commenting out the code block every update, but would it be possible to add a switch to disable this feature?<P>Apart from this info leaking at it's source another danger is inherent in sending these stop/start flags over the internet.<P>Call me paranoid but what is to stop a pro-mythic sysadmin that admins public network space from creating an extra IDS rule to log these stop/start packets and mail them to mythic?  A simple script could grep log files and send these to mythic automatically.<P>I think optimally a passive packet sniffer should be passive by default.  I appreciate all the work that slicer and others have put into this and I can see where the usage data might be interesting and rewarding.  OE sending out packets though does make me uncomfortable.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Rahvin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I'd have to agree, I think a toggle in the interface or commandline would be fine.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">DestinyX</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Talk about paranoid ...<P>- Edit -<P>And I think you can just take that part out of the code if you want to.<p>[This message has been edited by DestinyX (edited 12-18-2001).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Not a Warden!</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Good point, he could sell this data to Mythic so they can Perma ban most of the hackers...</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Froggy</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I really doubt that Mythic would ban people based soley on the content of keep alive packets. </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">J3K</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">YEh, I could run it locally and have a friend who plays DAoC get banned without him ever knowing I was running it... yay</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Slicer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sometimes the assumptions people take as facts amaze me.<BR>There are no keepalive packets. There are no start packets. There are no stop packets.<P>Read oeUpdate.cpp <P>There's a single HTTP GET of the current version of OE and the checksum of the maps, which is a HTTP file residing on <A HREF="http://www.hackersquest.org." TARGET=_blank>www.hackersquest.org.</A>  If you are paranoid (and stupid) enough to think I will sell log information to Mythic, you shouldn't be running OE in the first place, because OE contains BINARY components. I could have hidden anything in there, and you would never know.<P>If you still don't want to be visible in the hackersquest.org logs at all, first of all stop downloading anything from these pages, stop visiting these forums, and then type:<P>route add -host <A HREF="http://www.hackersquest.org" TARGET=_blank>www.hackersquest.org</A>  reject<P>on your OE machine to make sure OE doesn't view that webpage.<BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
